<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-238  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 238.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  Jan 1990 p23(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>All change for the 90s. (in manufacturing strategies)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Engineering has made major gains through the use of computer-aideddesign systems and office automation has increased productivity onthe desktop.andP;  Now manufacturing is turning to computerization as ameans of achieving improved inventory control and materials flow,better quality products and service, more accurate performancemeasures and a bridge between design and production.andP;  Companiesseeking competitive advantage must unite these elements in aclosed loop management system.andP;  Advantages of cost, productiontechnology, and product quality have evaporated and the onlyadvantage a company can be sure of is in the area of customerservice.andP;  Better customer service includes shorter cycle timesfrom procurement of materials to actual delivery to the customer.andO;The 90s will see companies succeed and survive that have theflexibility to make complex products in short cycle times andmanage the logistics involved.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Management StyleManufacturingAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Product life cycle costs. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>